Lengthy but comprehensive BBC version which I haven't seen again since it first aired. Once again, I'm sharing a movie review with my mother in mind. Given her appreciation for The Royal Tenenbaums, I believed she would also enjoy The Grand Budapest Hotel, but that proved to be a miscalculation. She endured the entire film, later comparing it unfavorably to her prolonged 24-hour labor experience with me. When the movie won four Oscars in 2015, her displeasure reached a boiling point, causing her to throw objects at the TV. As a direct result of this film, she has been boycotting hotels for the past 11 years.

Easily in my top favorite Wes Anderson films, The Grand Budapest Hotel is a fast-paced exploration of duty and class struggles, and alongside it's razor-sharp wit and unnervingly symmetrical shots, it's a true-to-form Anderson classique. TGBH has exceptionally memorable characters thanks to some mighty performances by their respective actors, and despite its impressive runtime it's a movie I find myself craving to watch again and again. Next to The Menu, this is definitely among Ralph Fiennes' best work to date.

Wong Kar-wai crafts a poetic and visually stunning martial arts epic. The cinematography is jaw-droppingâ€”each frame meticulously composed like a painting. His direction brings elegance and emotional weight to every scene, while the script and editing blend history and introspection seamlessly. The performances are mesmerizing, with Tony Leung anchoring the film in quiet power. Themes of legacy, identity, and sacrifice resonate deeply. A meditative and beautiful masterpiece.

(Chinese Cut)Beautifully crafted and performed, but itâ€™s also too formal and grand for its own good. Rarely does the film really feel like a WKW film, which of course isnâ€™t an inherently bad thing. Yet, it also restrains the film from being truly resonant. The fights kick ass at least.
